      "type": "answer",
      "text": "It's the third approach — **Frappe framework schemas as the blueprint, standalone Vue prototype that mirrors them 1:1**.\n\nSpecifically:\n\n- **No Frappe apps installed or running.** The prototype is entirely self-contained — Vue 3 + Vite + Tailwind, zero Frappe dependencies. It runs standalone at `localhost:8080`.\n\n- **Type definitions are researched from real Frappe repos** (gameplan, lms, raven, helpdesk, eps, payments). We pulled the actual `.json` DocType definitions from each repo's `main` branch and created TypeScript interfaces that mirror every field name, type, and option exactly. For example, `Raven Channel` uses `dm_user_1`/`dm_user_2` (not invented names), `HD Ticket` has `ticket_type` as `\"Bug\" | \"Feature\" | \"Service\" | \"Incident\"` matching the real Select options.\n\n- **Business logic is mocked in-memory** but follows Frappe patterns. The store's `createComment` mutates `GP Discussion.comments_count` and `last_post_at` the same way Frappe hooks would. `markLessonComplete` updates enrollment progress the same way LMS does. The pub/sub reactive store mimics Frappe's document event system.\n\n- **The production bridge (`src/data/store.ts`) is pre-wired** — every selector/mutator has the Frappe REST API endpoint logged in `console.log` when `IS_PRODUCTION_BACKEND` is true. When you deploy to a real Frappe bench, you swap the mock calls for the real `fetch` calls.\n\n- **The UI/UX is Circle.so-inspired** (the Lovable design), but the data model underneath is 100% Frappe. So the front-end looks like Circle, but porting to production is a search-and-replace of the mock store with real Frappe API calls — the types already match.\n\nIn short: **Circle.so UI layer + Frappe data model layer + standalone prototype that can plug into a real Frappe bench**.",
      "timestamp": 1781949061589
    },
    {
      "type": "thought",
      "text": "The user is asking about the approach taken for the prototype - whether we cherry-picked features from Frappe apps, implemented full versions and stripped down, or used Frappe framework with mix and match. This is a question about the architecture and design decisions, not a task to execute. Let me answer directly based on what I know from the project.\n\nLooking at the project, this is what happened:\n1. The project started as a Circle.so clone designed in Lovable (React)\n2. It was refactored to Vue 3 + Vite 8 + Tailwind v4\n3. The types were created to mirror real Frappe DocType field names 1:1\n4. It uses in-memory mock data today, with a production API bridge ready\n\nThe approach was:\n- Used real Frappe ecosystem DocType schemas (researched from actual .json files in the repos)\n\n\n- Designed the TypeScript interfaces to match those real schemas field-for-field, with the production API bridge prepared to connect to actual Frappe REST APIs\n- Built a standalone mock store that mirrors the business logic without implementing the full Frappe apps themselves\n\nSo it's really a third approach - leveraging Frappe's actual DocType schemas as the blueprint, creating a 1:1 TypeScript type mapping, and building a self-contained prototype that's ready to integrate with real Frappe endpoints.",
      "timestamp": 1781949064945
    },
    {
      "type": "user-query",
      "text": "why no frappe apps ?",
      "timestamp": 1781949200644
    },
    {
      "type": "answer",
      "text": "Because this is a **prototype/MVP**, not production.\n\nFrappe requires a full bench: Python, MariaDB/PostgreSQL, Redis, worker processes, nginx. That's heavy infrastructure for validating whether the product works and the UX is right.\n\nThe prototype exists to:\n- **Test the product** — does the community actually need polls, badges, mentoring, DMs?\n- **Validate UX** — does the Circle.so-style UI feel right for first-gen students?\n- **Iterate fast** — change a component, hot reload, see it instantly. No bench restart, no migrations.\n- **Get stakeholder buy-in** — show working screens, not wireframes.\n\nThe types are already 1:1 with real Frappe DocType field names so when you're ready for production, the port is mechanical:\n1. Set up a Frappe bench with gameplan, lms, raven, helpdesk, eps, payments\n2. Replace mock store calls with real API calls (the bridge already has the endpoints logged)\n3. No type changes needed — they already match\n\nIf you want to run actual Frappe apps now, that's a different conversation — I can help set up a bench environment.",
      "timestamp": 1781949200716
