      "output": "Title: Supporting students who are the first-generation in their family to attend university | FirstGens\nURL: https://firstgens.co.uk/\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nSupporting students who are the first-generation in their family to attend university | FirstGens\n...\n# The university experience can feel like walking in the dark. We exist to empower and support students who are the first-generation in their family to navigate university.\n...\nWe’re proud to be a multi-award-winning social enterprise making a difference nationwide. We unite a dynamic community of accomplished graduates from UK universities and a variety of careers. Together, we deliver workshops, create on-demand content, host panels, organise in-person events and offer mentoring.\n...\nOur platform has become an unmatched resource and network for first-generation undergraduates, providing valuable knowledge and support. We take a systems-change approach, by delivering corporate training and campaigns, designed to raise awareness and eliminate barriers in higher education.\n...\n## We are working towards a world where every young person, irrespective of their background, has access to vital tools, resources, and networks needed to turn their aspirations into reality.\n...\nData shows that two-thirds of undergraduates are first-generation students attending university and pursuing graduate jobs. Over the past four years, we have worked directly with students to understand why persistent national gaps in outcomes exist.\n...\nDuring the cost of living crisis, we facilitated £10,000 in grants provided to first-generation students from low-income households.\n\n---\n\nTitle: FirstGens – Medium\nURL: https://medium.com/@FirstGens\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nFirstGens – Medium\n\nSign up\n\nGet app\n\nSign up\n\nFirstGens\n\n## Tips for Living with Roommates in University Housing\n\n### Living with roommates in university housing can be an exciting and rewarding experience. You get to share your living space with other…\n\nNov 12, 2025\n\nNov 12, 2025\n\n## Working During University: Expectations vs Realities\n\n### The summer preceding my start at university was one of 70-hour or 80-hour weeks, with irregular diets, and sleep deprivation. As…\n\nAug 26, 2025\n\nAug 26, 2025\n\n## A Marathon, Not a Sprint: Building Self-Confidence at University\n\n### Self-confidence is one of the most important assets you can have as you navigate through university life and the working world beyond…\n\nAug 26, 2025\n\nAug 26, 2025\n\n## Boosting Budgets as a First-generation\n\n### Being a university student can be an exciting time in your life, filled with new experiences and opportunities. However, it can also be a…\n\nAug 26, 2025\n\nAug 26, 2025\n\n## The Real Cost of University: Understanding Hidden Expenses\n\n### University is a time of growth, learning, and exploration. It’s also a time when many students experience financial stress. While the cost…\n\nAug 14, 2025\n\nAug 14, 2025\n\n## Podcasts for First-generation Students\n\n### I\n\nAug 14, 2025\n\nAug 14, 2025\n\n## How To Look After Your Health and Wellbeing at University\n\n### University is a time of great change and transition, which can be both exciting and overwhelming for many students. Whilst it’s important…\n\nAug 14, 2025\n\nAug 14, 2025\n\n## Charlotte Church’s The Dreaming — An inclusive approach to wellbeing\n\n### Recently, FirstGens Founder, Alaya Holloway, was invited by Charlotte Church’s The Dreaming to experience their Rhydoldog House — a…\n\nJan 7, 2025\n\nJan 7, 2025\n\n## Our Rebrand, Our Growth, Our Future. This is FirstGens 2.0\n\n### Welcome to a brand new website! Literally, because FirstGens rebranded. The response has been one of cheer and excitement. But it also…\n\nDec 18, 2024\n\nDec 18, 2024\n\n## How does accent bias affect university students and what steps can organisations take to mitigate…\n\n### Written by Ambassador Amber Hadley, University of Cambridge Postgraduate.\n\nNov 19, 2024\n\nNov 19, 2024\n\n## FirstGens\n\nEmpowering students who are the first generation in their family to pursue university.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Universities | FirstGens\nURL: https://firstgens.co.uk/work-with-us/universities\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nUniversities | FirstGens\n...\nThe First-generation metric is the most predictive indicator of those less likely to attend HE. This should be included in the conversation when talking about widening university participation. When we widen participation, we need to ensure diverse student talent is retained.\n...\nWe collaborated with design experts and first-generation students to curate a student-centric programme addressing the root causes of first-generation student challenges, helping students avoid common unexpected hurdles.\n...\nOur 6-month program invites your students to engage in structured activities designed to foster a sense of belonging and provide timely information and guidance through our bespoke curriculum, the Navigating University Roadmap. These activities help reduce the common first 3-week dropout rates.\n...\nOur programme offers a well-structured series of activities for first-generation students. Participants receive a comprehensive workbook and access to on-demand content through a single sign-on digital platform. This setup ensures scalability, enabling universities to effectively support large cohorts of first-generation students.\n...\nTo support university staff, we deliver a learning and development webinar, combining secondary research with unique insights discovered from FirstGens' internal surveys and focus groups. This session offers experiences, thoughts and ideas shared by first-generation students across the UK.\n...\n“I wanted to gain insight into the experiences of first gen students and learn about how we can better assist/advise and support. The training was really informative. I appreciated the integration of real life statistics and comments from students. Alaya was a fantastic, welcoming and knowledgable\n...\nthe topic. A great flagbearer for First-generation students\n...\nEvents Discover our events dedicated to the advancement of outcomes for first-generation students. These events serve as a platform for thought leadership, initiating discussions to promote equity in higher education.\n...\nuniversity. When it comes from FirstGens, you pay extra attention because you know they are looking out for you and have your best interest in mind. Through the programme, I received a bursary which I wouldn't have seen had I not been told through\n...\n“As a first-generation student with two parents in non-professional careers, I often recognise differences between the support and resources available to my friends with parents who aren't first-generation students. I love the aim of this organisation and feel that this work is vital.”\n...\nFirstGens has taught\n...\nresilient and proud of\n\n---\n\nTitle: Mighty Good Agency - FirstGen Forward\nURL: https://www.mightygoodagency.com/projects/firstgen-forward\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nAs the nation’s leading association for student affairs professionals, NASPA has long championed strategies that support first-generation college students. These “FirstGen” students represent the majority of all undergraduates today, yet continue to graduate at lower rates than their peers. With FirstGen experiences and outcomes capturing increased attention across the education sector, NASPA teamed up with long-time FirstGen advocates, The Suder Foundation, to develop a suite of programs that help colleges and universities better serve FirstGen students. To further the impact of their programs, the two partners engaged Mighty Good to strengthen their programs’ branding.\n...\nFollowing an extensive research process, Mighty Good identified that the various programs could more successfully serve as an intuitive system of support for institutions of higher education as well as students, by streamlining disconnected branded entities. So, Mighty Good developed a brand architecture that linked the work under one brand system, FirstGen Forward, and one shared tagline, “The Future is FirstGen”. This unified identity and language was designed to highlight the size of the FirstGen population, and the widespread implications for FirstGen student success.\n...\nTo ensure the FirstGen Forward visual identity system was as vibrant and youthful as the population it represents, Mighty Good employed bright, diverse, and energetic colors with confident structure, humanized with student imagery. Throughout the system, bold lines move through the space to symbolize the new pathways that FirstGen students forge as they move through higher education and into the future.\n...\nTo evoke the organization’s leadership on behalf of the FirstGen population, Mighty Good created a logo mark that employs a unique fusion of “F” and “G” letters into one symbol, with the “F” formed from the negative space inside the “G”. The result is a clean, distinct, bold symbol\n\nthat can be used on its own in a variety of ways.\n...\nUnder the new brand system, the signature program to help higher education institutions transform into FirstGen-supportive campuses, was renamed from First Scholars to the FirstGen Forward Network. Mighty Good revamped the program’s “designation badge” system to acknowledge high performing campuses, incentivize other institutions to follow suit, and help prospective students be more informed consumers.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Brand & Style Guide (Download)\nURL: https://www.firstgensociety.org/articles/firstgen-society-brand-amp-style-guide-download\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nBrand & Style Guide (Download)\n\n# Brand & Style Guide (Download)\n\nBack\n\n# JOIN THE MISSION\n\nWould you like to help contribute and make a difference within the first generation college student community? We are currently looking for ambitious Founding Members to join our national social organization who share our vision and want to contribute and help us build the foundation of FirstGen Society.\n\nAt FirstGen Society, we share common identity of being a first generation college student and are dedicated to building an incredible community where we can inspire growth, empower others, and connect first generation college students and alumni on a national level.\n\n##### Let's connect, empower, and grow together!\n\nJoin Us\n\n---",
